# AI Tool & Recipe Architecture

The assistant is **tool-using**. Every user turn flows through one pipeline:

```
User Prompt
   │
   ▼
selectTool()        ← ONE inference call: model sees tool definitions (with
   │                   param schemas), picks the tool, and extracts arguments
   │                   Output: {"tool":"change_theme","args":{"theme_name":"Starter"}}
   │
   ▼
executeWithConfirmation()  ← gates mutating tools when interactionMode is "ask"
   │
   ▼
tool.run(ctx)       ← the tool executes with pre-extracted ctx.args
   │
   ▼
dispatcher          ← commits result to history, injects context if remember=true
```

## File Structure (modular)

```
src/
├── sidepanel/
│   ├── index.ts            # Entry point: wires engine, tools, UI, state
│   ├── types.ts            # Shared interfaces (Tool, ToolContext, ToolResult, etc.)
│   ├── state.ts            # App state, storage keys, persistence helpers
│   ├── engine-client.ts    # Engine port management, runChat, runInference
│   ├── tool-registry.ts    # Tool registration, selection prompt, selectTool()
│   ├── confirmation.ts     # "Ask before acting" confirmation gate
│   ├── markdown.ts         # Lightweight Markdown → HTML renderer
│   ├── image-utils.ts      # Image downscale, file reading, drag-and-drop
│   └── tools/
│       ├── index.ts        # Re-exports all tools
│       ├── create-presentation.ts
│       ├── change-theme.ts
│       ├── screenshot.ts
│       ├── doccontext.ts
│       ├── slidecontext.ts
│       └── chat.ts         # Default "none" tool (general conversation)
├── zoho/
│   └── api.ts              # All Zoho Show API interactions (centralized)
├── background.ts           # Service worker: relay, CDP, Zoho script injection
├── content.ts              # DOM agent: collectElements, executeAction
├── offscreen.ts            # wllama engine: model load, chat, agentStep
├── messages.ts             # Typed inter-context message protocol
├── models.ts               # Model config + context size options
├── modes.ts                # Effort modes (flash/focus/forge/max)
├── actions.ts              # Agent action types + JSON parsing
├── recipes.ts              # Recipe definitions and step types
├── prompts.ts              # System prompts (chat, agent, summarization)
├── session.ts              # Engine-owned session state + compaction
├── themes.ts               # Theme catalogue + lookup helpers
├── slide-data.ts           # Parse Zoho slide/master data
├── debug-log.ts            # Debug log panel
└── stripThinking.ts        # Strip Qwen thinking tags
```

## Adding a New Tool

1. Create `src/sidepanel/tools/your-tool.ts`:

```typescript
import type { Tool, ToolContext, ToolResult } from "../types";

export const yourTool: Tool = {
  name: "your_tool",
  description: "user wants to … (be specific and mutually exclusive vs others)",
  params: [
    { name: "target", type: "string", description: "what to act on", required: true },
  ],
  mutating: true,  // set true if it changes the presentation
  async run(ctx: ToolContext): Promise<ToolResult | null> {
    const target = ctx.args.target;
    ctx.setStatus("Working…");
    if (ctx.isStopped()) return null;
    // … do work, render into ctx.replyEl …
    return { assistantText: "what happened", remember: true };
  },
};
```

2. Export from `src/sidepanel/tools/index.ts`
3. Register in `src/sidepanel/index.ts` tools array

That's it. The tool selection prompt is auto-generated from the registry.

## Action Hierarchy (when to use what)

1. **Zoho API calls** (via `zoho/api.ts`) — fastest, most reliable. Use when an
   internal API exists (changeTheme, getSlideData, createPresentation).
2. **Recipes** (`recipes.ts`) — deterministic step sequences. Use when no API exists
   but steps are predictable.
3. **Agent loop** (`actions.ts` + observe/act) — model-driven DOM interaction. Only
   for truly open-ended navigation where steps can't be predicted.

## Confirmation Flow

Tools marked `mutating: true` are gated by `executeWithConfirmation()` when
`interactionMode === "ask"`. The confirmation dialog shows what will happen and
requires explicit user approval before proceeding.

## Key Principles

- **Single-call routing** — one inference call selects the tool AND extracts args.
- **AI decides, code executes** — the model picks; hard-coded code acts.
- **Single source of truth** — `tools[]` array drives prompt, schema, and dispatch.
- **Centralized Zoho API** — all Zoho interactions go through `zoho/api.ts`.
- **Confirmation before mutation** — mutating tools respect interactionMode.
- **Live state over memory** — fetch live data instead of relying on chat memory.
